---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro'
import Header from '../components/Header.tsx'
import '../index.css'
---

<Layout title="About - PhyloGuessr">
  <div class="game">
    <Header client:load />
    <div class="about-page">
      <h2>About PhyloGuessr</h2>

      <h3>How it works</h3>
      <p>Pick which two of three organisms are most closely related — the pair sharing the most recent common ancestor.</p>

      <h3>Data sources</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Taxonomy from <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/taxonomy" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">NCBI Taxonomy</a></li>
        <li>Images from <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Wikipedia</a></li>
      </ul>

      <h3>A note on polytomies</h3>
      <p>NCBI Taxonomy is a classification, not a phylogeny — it sometimes can't resolve which two of three species are closest (a "polytomy"). When this happens, any answer is accepted as correct. In rare cases where phylogenetic studies have resolved the relationship, we note this in the fun fact.</p>

      <h3>Contribute</h3>
      <p><a href="https://github.com/cmdcolin/phyloguessr" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">GitHub</a> · <a href="https://github.com/cmdcolin/phyloguessr/issues" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Report bugs or suggest trios</a></p>

      <h3>Why phylogeny matters</h3>
      <p>Phylogeny — the evolutionary relationships among species — underpins much of biology.</p>

      <h4>Applied sciences</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>Drug discovery — picking model organisms closest to humans</li>
        <li>Agriculture — finding wild relatives for crop breeding</li>
        <li>Epidemiology — tracking pathogen evolution and spread</li>
        <li>Antibiotic resistance — tracing resistance gene spread across bacteria</li>
        <li>Forensics — linking biological evidence to its source</li>
        <li>Conservation — prioritizing evolutionarily unique lineages</li>
        <li>Bioprospecting — finding useful compounds by screening relatives of known producers</li>
      </ul>

      <h4>Genomics and molecular biology</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>Comparative genomics — predicting gene function from related species</li>
        <li>Ancestral reconstruction — inferring ancient proteins and traits</li>
        <li>Orthologs vs. paralogs — distinguishing speciation from duplication events</li>
        <li>Horizontal gene transfer — detecting genes that jumped between species</li>
        <li>Molecular clocks — dating when lineages diverged</li>
        <li>Metagenomics — classifying organisms in environmental DNA samples</li>
      </ul>

      <h4>Ecology and evolution</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>Taxonomy — defining and naming species within an evolutionary framework</li>
        <li>Biogeography — explaining species distributions across the globe</li>
        <li>Community ecology — understanding how species assemblages form</li>
        <li>Coevolution — studying reciprocal adaptations between hosts and parasites</li>
        <li>Adaptive radiation — understanding how lineages rapidly diversify into new niches</li>
        <li>Trait evolution — reconstructing when traits like flight, venom, or photosynthesis arose or were lost</li>
        <li>Convergent evolution — identifying traits that evolved independently in unrelated lineages</li>
        <li>Phylogeography — tracing how populations spread and diverged across geography</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
</Layout>
